Dear Families,

     What a wonderful surprise we had this morning!  Thank you for the
lovely videos of your children and the kind words.  We definitely feel the
love.  We are very lucky teachers to have such thoughtful children and
families.  Thank you.

Just a reminder about work in writing...



   -

    Please send along your child=E2=80=99s book review video (if they choos=
e to
   make one).  The ones we=E2=80=99ve received so far are fantastic!  It wo=
uld be
   fun to have a few more to compile and share.



   -

   On Monday, kids will be prompted to write independently for 30 minutes
   about a given topic.  For us to =E2=80=9Ctake stock,=E2=80=9D we are hop=
ing to have samples
   of writing that reflect what kids are able to do on their own.  This is
   something we typically do in the classroom at the start or end of a writ=
ing
   unit as a formative assessment (meaning it will inform us in planning ou=
r
   next writing unit).  It is not graded and not shared.  Once your child h=
as
   worked on their writing prompt independently for 30 minutes, please emai=
l
   me a photo of their work.  Thank you in advance!


Writing and Feedback

     A couple folks have asked about feedback on children=E2=80=99s work.  =
You are
always more than welcome to send work for me to review.  I will comment and
send it back.  It can be a little tricky to get specific when =E2=80=9Ctalk=
ing
feedback=E2=80=9D in our small groups, as I can=E2=80=99t really see the wo=
rk.  I can
appreciate that it is quite difficult to give feedback as a parent as
well!  Overall, we value building confidence and self-expression.  If your
child is open to hearing some feedback from you, you might use some of the
ideas below (but please don=E2=80=99t try these out until Tuesday, as we wa=
nt
Monday=E2=80=99s writing session to be truly independent):

Talking About Writing with Kids:

   -

   Compliments! Start with a compliment!
   -

      Think big picture (e.g. =E2=80=9CYou got right to work today!=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9CI noticed you
      really worked on your introduction.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CYou gave lots o=
f reasons/details.=E2=80=9D
      =E2=80=9CYour picture really helps me understand what you are talking=
 about.=E2=80=9D)



   -

   Ask questions you don't know the answer to such as:
   -

      =E2=80=9CWhat's your favorite part?=E2=80=9D
      -

      =E2=80=9CHow do you think this is going?=E2=80=9D
      -

      =E2=80=9CWhat are you working on in this writing?=E2=80=9D



   -

   Next Steps: If your child is responsive to your input, maybe try one of
   these.

       ** Please note that these are statements, not questions.  If you
ask, =E2=80=9CIs there something else you could add?=E2=80=9D the answer wi=
ll almost always
be, =E2=80=9CNo.=E2=80=9D

   -

   =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s find one place where you can add more.=E2=80=9D
   -

   =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s reread what you wrote yesterday.=E2=80=9D
   -

   =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s reread and check all the sight/trick words we alr=
eady know.=E2=80=9D



   -

   If kids are feeling stuck...
   -

      Let it go.  It is hard to get kids to write and writing is a hard
      task.  Taking a break is okay!
      -

      Draw.  Drawing is writing.  Draw or sketch to plan for a writing
      topic, or just draw about the topic.
      -

      I write, you write.  =E2=80=9CTag team=E2=80=9D sentences or have you=
r child
      dictate.
      -

      Label pictures or use speech bubbles.


     Thank you for all the work you=E2=80=99ve been doing with your kids; y=
ou=E2=80=99re
doing great!

Have a restful weekend.

